he Dainty Candy Sh\nREED MILLER, Proprietor 443 Main St.\nP A D T AMOT3ARSTR ST OV T T R RT S TR M\nI e r\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014e s o\u2014\u2014.\n\nJ\nPhone, Jot. 380\nWatch for the\nWhite Wagons\nLAUNDRY\nT\u2014\u2014 e S %Te e o B .e e e ee i e .t et\nee e e\nREAL ESTATE BARGAINS el\n2\nWe control and offer for sale on easy terms a few dwellings in\nGrand Junction, Clifton and Fruita, which are foreclosed properties\n2 and will be disposed of for the amount of the mortgeges. We have\nhouses in prices from $BOO up., This is an excellent chance to se\ncure a home on instalment payments at loan -values,\no We control and offer fur sile choice ranch properties in the val\nley and Plateau Valley. Our connections in Plateau Valley are\nsuch as enable us to give the best possible information and assist\ns\ufb02; %,,huygr\u2019p. \u2018This is the coming great dairy scction of Col\norado. B i B o M G eoil e\nThis is the time of year to check over your insurance. We\nDhave been in the business for 24 years, and every loss in our\n(o %%\ufb02l'gy'@u been sgatisfactorily adjusted.\nol e free\nwrrall. N\nTHE HOME LOAN IRVESTMENT GO, 357 MAW ST,\nTE T i i RSR R S R\nTrades Ranch.\nn A. T. Bigler has traded his city\nproperty and ranch east of the city\nfor residence property in Colorado\nSprings, and expects to move across\nllthe range in a few weeks. Mr. Big\ni ler came to the valley from northwest\nlown a dozen years ago and the\nL friends of the family will regret to\nL |eee them depart.\nD. T Grote of Wyoming lis in\nB !(.'rund Junction and the Grand valley,\nIvisiting relatives and friends.\nI.W.W TRIES OLD\nGAME IN PORTLAND\n]lndustnal Workers Storm Res\ny Did in\nGrand Junction,\n|.~\u00a7ssurhncd Press,\nPortland, Ore., Deec, 23.\u2014Two res\n;lmxr:mm were stormed today by\n'gangs of men led by Industrial Work\n}vrs of the World, who announced\n\u2018that they were without money and\nmust be fed,\nIn the first case fourteen men\n,murched into a cafeteria, ate a sub\n;slunllul meal and then announced\nthat they could not and would not\n]pn_\\'. The manager hailed a passing\npoliceman and the men ran. \u201cThe of\nficer arrested three, who were lock\ned up on charges of disorderly con\nduct,\nLater forty men walked into a res\ntaurant and demanded to be served,\nsaying \u201cMayor Albee will pay for it.\u201d\nTwenty police reserves were sum\nmoned, and after a stormy scene the\nmen were ejected. None was ar\nrested,\nThe men threatened to repeat\ntheir exploit at other places and po\nlice guards are posted at many res\ntaurants tonight,\nil b\nFOURTEEN CLASSES ENTER\nY. M. C. A. BOWLING LEAGUE\ni Sunday school bowling league at\n\u2018the Y. M. C. A, has had entries from\nfeurteen classes and two more will\n}be added from present prospects,\nIt is the purpose of Y. M. C. A. to\ngive this privilege to the Sunday\n\u2018school clagses without any cost and\none of the strong features of the\nleague is the fact that members add\ned to the classes will be one of the\nfactors in the scoring of points,\nThe schedule of the games will be\npublished in a short time for the\nserjes which will start on January 5.\nHere on Visit,\nN. B, Coles, former city attorney,\ncame in this morning on No. 3 to\nspend a month with his family be\nitorc returning to his large cattle\nranch at Maropis, in Moffit county.\nMr. Coles has a very large circle of\nfriends, who will be glad to hear\nthat he is in Grand Junction.\ni BUCK HORN CORRAL.\nGood corral and camp house.\n'Team on hay over night........80\u00a2\n\u2018Team on hay grain overnight $1.20\nCome and see us. We want your\n\u2018trade. Give us a trial. We will treat\n*yon right. Rooms to rent.\nCorral, 617 Pitkin avenue.\nI Phone Junction 463,\ni MATTINGLY BROS,,\n12-22-Gt Proprietors.\nR S\nSERIOUS CATARRA\nYIELDS TO HYOMEI\ne o TS R NN o\nl Do not let this serious disease ex\nilund along the delicate mucous mem\nbrane, gradually going from the nose\n|to the throat, thence into the bron\nchial tubes and downward into the\ni lungs,\nThere is no other treatment for ca\ntarrh that is like Hyomei or just as\ngood. None can take its place, none\ngive such quick, effective and sure re\nlief and at so little cost\u2014furthermore\nthe C. D. Smith Drug Co. will re\nfund your money if you are not sat\nigtied.\nBegin using Hyomei now \u2014}uduy-\u2014\u2014\nand see how quickly the droppings in\nto the throat, the discharge from the\nnose, sniffling and all other symp\ntoms of catarrh are overcome; and\nremember-\u2014no stomach drugging\u2014\nyou breathe it. The complete outfit\ncontaining inhaler and Dbottle of\nliquid costs but SI.OO. Extra bot\ntles of liquid, it luter needed, 00\ncents,\nTHE GRAND JUNCTION UAILY SENTINEL.\nABOUT HOME FOLKS\nand\nABOUT HOME DOINGS\n(By A, C. NEWTON.)\nAbout this time of the year a good\nmany boxes of fancy Grand valley\napples are semt out to friends in\neastern states as Christmas presents,\nand there is no better or more appro\npriate reminder of the day than this,\nbut there would be a great many\nmore boxes sent out were it not for\nthe outrageous, unjust and discrim:-\nnating charges made by the express\ncompanies, and there is no greater\nopportunity for r\u00e9gulation by the\nInterstate Commerce Commission or\nthe State Railroad Commission thaa\nthat of the express rates.\nA box of apples can be sent to New\nYork City for a little less than $2, yet\n'you can not send one to Pittsburgh or\n\u2019lo any other city in Pennsylvania for\nless than $3.70; in other words a\nbox of apples will pass right througn\nPittsburgh, and hundreds of miles\n\u2018fllrth(\"r east for $1.75 less money.\nThis is the case in hundreds of in\nstances. There is nothing but the\nnigh merchandise rate to any point\nin Indiana or to any point in the\nsouthern states, and there is a total\nlack of system and a general mixup\nof tariffs all over the United States,\nand seemingly there has been so\nmuch profit in the express business\nthat the managers have not had time\nto prepare for anything like a sys\niu:matic system.\nJust why the National Railroad\nCommission has not taken up this\n\u2018branch of the public utilities is very\nhard to understand; we were told\nthat a new rate would go into effect\nthe first of October, and then it was\npostponed until the first of Novem\nber, and we have not heard anything\nabout the matter since; what is\nneeded is a national regulation with\nrates to common points and the same\nrate to govern all other points at a\nlike distance, without the addition\nof the loecal tariffs from those com\nmon points. Then it would not take\na half hour to discover what the rate\nig to any point in the United Slul('-.l\nThere is now a fruit rate to a fow\nlocalities, and just why this rate does\nnot apply to all points is beyoud the\nken of the wisest man.\nAgain we ought to have regulation\nright here in Colorado, and our rail\nway commission cught to have some\nthing to say relative to the practice\nof charging just as much to Lead\nville as to Denver, yet we have not\nheard of a single thing that our\nrailway commission has done the past\n12 months, or since the supreme\ncourt ruled that it had the power lu\u2019\nfix rates, The public utilities law\nwould have given clear and emphatic\npower to that ecommission had it not\nbeen for a few men who sought to|\npostpone its action for two years by\nreferring that mfnure\u2018 It was clear\nand specific on the points of regula\ntion of all utilities. No doubt the\ncommission is, still pulling down\nsaiaries.\nOne would think that the cxpressk\ncompanies are interested su\ufb02ir\u2018ionl]yl\n\u2018ln the development of this new coun\ntry to carefully watch the trend of\nsentiment, and not wait to be forced\nby parcels post or drastic laws into\ndoing what they should to protect\nthe industries upon which not only\nthe prosperity of the companies mustl\nrely, but the prosperity of the entire\nsection of country on this western\nslope,\nIt is indeed most unfortunate that\nthe entire fruit shipping arrnnge\u2014l\nments of this valley could not have\nbeen united under one management.\nThe failure to do so means that there\nwill be at least 10\u00a2 profit on every\nbox of fruit go to expense. This in\nitself would be a fair margin of prof\nit over what the growers are receiv\ning at present. Every sensible man\nknows that the added expense of man\nagement means at least 5S\u00a2 per box,\nand Manager Fletcher has said that\nthere would be no trouble in secur\ning at least 5\u00a2 per box at the selling\nend, if one management controlled\nthe entire output. The benefit of\nhaving a large crop of all varieties\nof fruit in order to be able to supply\nevery market demand would also be\na very great help as to selling.\nIt is unfortunate that negotiations\nhave been terminated because wita\neach meeting there might come con\ncessions on either side and a conse\nquent agreement. It is impossible. no\ndoubt, to get all the growers in line,\nbut it ought to be possible to get a\nvery large majority of them together,\nand it wili come some day after the\ngrowers have lest enough money.\nWiiliam Harrison, the new horti\nculturalist for the county, is trying to\norganize a county horticultural so\nciety; we had such a society a dozen\nvears ago when the matter of deal\ning with the codling moth and other\npests first struck our growers, and\nfor a time there was an active inter\nest taken with meetings all over the\nvalley. For the most part the at\ntendance was confined to those grow\ners who were anxious to learn and\nhad made the pests a careful study;\nthey were willing to meet and dis\ncuss local conditions. and very much\nzood was acconplished, but in tiue\nthe interest fell off and the live\ngrowers could not afford to moet\nand talk to empty seats.\nNo doubt we shall have those same\ninterested growers who are keeping\nup with the times present at the\nmeetings to be called, but the move\nment is not so much for such growers\nas for those who are not up-to-date,\nbut who are bowailing the fact that\nthere is no way to defeat the work of\nthe pests, and that fruit-growing is\na ~m;urg. LAt .all .of ,tuf: .\u2018;npeuxg\nthere should be hundreds'of grow\npresent who need to know all about\norchard and tmixp \u2018work. If they do\nattend they wil %:d plenty of local\nmen present who can tell them what\n\u2018they are doing to make a success of\napples, peaches and pears; polatoes,\nwheat, corn, hogs, cattle and the fer\ntilization and dMe of the land.\nI have an idea \u2018there are men in\nthis vailey who are better acquainted\nwith the conditions here than the\nmen from Fort Collins, and it only\nneeds college men to start the ball\nrolling. I trust there will be a sur\nprise in store for me in the attend\n\u2019nnce of the meetings soon to be\ncalled.\nIn accord with my idea that it is\ndue largely to the intelligent and\npainstaking work, and also the busi\nness-like management of our or\nchards that the highest degree of suc\ncess depends, I wish to call attention\n'to the work of Mr, C. B. Fletcher of\n\u2018Orchard Mesa, who two years ago\ncame to the valley from Cherokee,\n\u2018la., and bought an orchard on Or\nchard Mesa, which previously had not\nbeen cared for properly and was not\ntn success. This year Mr. Fletcher\nwent to work with the same degree\n\u2018of study and care which he exhibited\n\\tor many years as one of the division\n'superintendents of the Illinois Cen\n\u2018tral railroad. He personally attend\ned to the bands on his trees and held\n'the spray nozzle, besides doing all the\n~other work attendant on caring for\nthe 10 acres.\nBut a small part of this orchard is\nin active bearing, and the balance\n?needs grafting and changing as to|\n\u2018varieties, but from his bearing prop\n\u2018erty this year he harvested about\n11,100 boxes of apples and 250 boxes\n!of pears which returned a net of\nlabout $1,400. This for the first year\n'is most excellent ,and is a fair cri\n\u2018terion of what can be done by oune\n'who knows nothing about orchard\n\\work, If he will but give it the ben\n:eflt of study, such as he would give!\n'to a railroad proposition. Mr. Fletch\n|er is delighted with the work and can\n'do much better as the years go by.\nHe is the father of Mr. Howard G.\nFletcher of the Grand Junction as\nsociatioh, and the writer met hlm}\nmany years ago in the Masonic lodge\nIrooms in his lowa city.\n\u2014_\u2014\nThere is an interesting fact de\nveloped this year or Orchard Mesa\n4\u00a7 to the failure of the pear crop in\n'the orchards of Messrs. Zellars and\nHill which have always heretofore\n\u2018had a good crop, but this year were\nalmost an eatire failure, while the\norcharda all about them had the best\ncrop in years. There must be some\n\u2018reason for the conditions as these\ntwo orchards are close together, and\nit will be interesting to study out\n\u2018l\u2018no conditions existing there and\n\u2018which frequently happens in other\nlocalities.\nWonder what would happen to\nRoady Kenehan if the miners\u2019 fed\neration should seek to recall Govern\nor Ammons and should put Roady up\nfor its candidate? The position of\nGovernor Ammons is a very difficult\none, indeed; he is trying to prevent\nbloodshed in the coal camps whether\nit is due to the miners or to the lo\ncal guards; the miners made one\nfatal mistake in the outset in pro-\u2018\nviding themselves with fire arms;\nthey were intended for but one pur\npose\u2014to prevent the working of the\nmines and for use, and not {or orna\n\u2018ment,\n\u2014_\u2014\nDespite this fact there is a wide\nspread regret that there should be\non this holiday season any body of\nlaboring men idle and forced to do\nwithout many of the comforts and\nluxuries of the season when right in\nsight of them there is work to do\nand money to pay for it. No doubt\nthe miners have many reasons to\nfind fault, but gradually through the\nenforcement of law, the conditions\nare improving, and if we could just\neliminate the professional labor agi\ntator and install in place of him care\nfully chosen officials whose sole aim\nis the enforcement of the laws for\nthe better conditions of the mines,\nand not political ax grinders, we|\nshould have prosperity and happi-l\nness in the mining secticns not found\nin other localities of the state.\ne e\nDistributes Turkeys,\nChief Dispatclier Hopkins has re\nceived a barrel of fine turkeys this,\nmorning from the Montrose sectlnn\u2018\nand is distributing them among his\nfriends. The barrel contained a doz\nen fat ones.\nA\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\nThanks lcm\\)loyes.\nJ. F. Bnright, superintendent of\nthe motive and power departments\nat the local yards, has taken the op\nportunity afforded by the Christmas\nseason to thank all his employes for\nthe splendid way in which they have\ndone their work the past year.\nR e\n32 Below at Steamboat,\nJ. F. McKinnie arrived in this city\nyesterday morning from S'.uumhoat|\nSprings. He spent yesterday looking\nover the valley, and was much pleas\ned with it. This morning, accompan\nied by his wife, he left for Whitewa\nter, where he will spend Christmas\nwith relatives. Mr. McKinnie states\nthat it was 2 below at his home when\nhe left. He will return there in a\nfew days.\nSR P R\nWill Play Boulder,\nA definite announcement was made\nthis morning by the Y. M. C. A. that\ni the local team will play the Unlversb}\nty Five from Boulder next Tuesday\nevening at 8 o'clock, at the \u201cY\" gym.\nLast night a meeting was held to de-l\ncide-whether it was advisable. Every\none concerned wished to pay and so\nthe gamo was scheduled. The \u201c\u2018Y\"'|\na:;ys elected for their captain E.\nertz. They will begin to practice\ntonight.\nel L S i T\nMrs. Frank Alderson stopped off\nhere yvesterday en route from Bagle\nDelta to.spend the Christmas hol\n\u2018W \u201cA\ufb01dgkglct,lves.\u2018sl;a\nco on her way this morning.\nPUBLIC SALE.\n1 will sell at public auction at the\n{FREE CORRAL at 1 o'clock Satur\n|day, Dec. 27, 25 head of mileh cows.\nE. W. SPENCER,\n12-2413 t Owner.\nWEDNESDAY EVENING, DECEMBER 24, 191\nL1 L T R T 4\nE e e e\u2014\u2014\u2014\nSD T Vg P ey SRR et 1Y \u2019\ufb02&\ufb01v\nNires e g ey\ni, *M e 2 <3 i 3,;\nji ~7?\\3 33\\1\u2019.\u20180,- =R T N LSB\\ e\nWe thank you for the liberal patronage you have\nfavored us with and wish you all\ng\n\nA MERRY l\nCHRISTMAS l\nI RW3ATR SR T O A\n\nOpen until 9 o'clock this evening\nClosed all day Christmas\nCPHONES \"R DRLAN IR BN \"PHONE\neoo EL',H, L 8 4 3 R %IR p\nli:\u2018if; Mz\u2019 M\ufb02f JJCTHZ\nFHGEOB. THINGS TO. EAFY\nManicure Rolls and Cases for Hol- \ufb01lurfz;n[at;tisr \u2018forr \u201c*0]'1(!;\u2018;\"(;(}.3 in\ndiay remembrances. The C. D. Smith colors and white. The C. D. Smith\nDrug Company Stores. 16 Drug Company Stores, 16\nRR B L SGR A A A R R A GG\nThe Perfect Christmas Gift\nAARTR I AT R TAR D A CTAL R TR T AL T A T R S\ng The mellow radiance and glowing warmth of a beauti\nful electric lamp will reflect the cheery spirit of Yuletide\nthroughout the new year and years to come.\n3 We have for your selection, Library Lamps, Piano\nLamps, Desk Lamps, Boudoir Lamps, Floor Lamps, and\nDining Room Domes from $8.590 to $27.00.\nElectric Heating Appliances\n\nTHE ELECTRIC SHOP\n4th and Colorado Phone Junction 46\ne M e e e e B eo e\ns\nAt Frederick\u2019s Post Office Book Store\nand Grand Junction Book Store\nConklin Fountain Pens, always fully guaranteed.\nThe following Books, all at REDUCED PRICES:\nThe famous Alger series for Boys_.________________2s\u00a2\nTom Swifteseniestio Pt o ity Sne s e g B\nBoy SeouitiSeries s Sagaeic iit T S B 0 RG\nRovar=Boys'ssegies obcuiios -t ba o BiE NS\nPopular Bietion=- <T oo vefo dven il Wit sR KN\n(Formerly $1.50.)\nLeather Pillows and Pennants\nCalendars from__________________________ls\u00a2 to $1.50\nLargest and Best Line in the City.\nFancy Christmas Cards, and the Largest Line of Christmas\nPost Cards in the City.\n\u201cM\n'W\nCoal at Reduced Price\nNow is the time to fill your bins. $3.25 in yard.\n$8.75 delivered. At the\nRIVERSIDE PALISADE COAL YARD\nW.H PLATO\n615 South Avenue Phone, Junction 257\nM?\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014 \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014e\nT T R st\nSPU G\u2014How about an up-to-the-minute buggy or sur\nrey for the family as a Christmas gift? Or a rich, warm\nlap-robe, or a cozy foot warmer for cold weather drives?\nWe have these and a host of other useful things suitable for\ngifts, and which would be appreciated by the entire family.\nMcCARY\n\u2014e MR S e\nROY, UTAH\nWe grow all kinds of Fruit, Shade and Ornamental Trees.\nCurrants, Grapes and Berries of all kinds. Roses Vines,\n3 and shrubs,\nCAPT. MILES STANDISH, AGT.\n645 Maln Street Grand Junction, Colo\n\u2014_\u2014_\u2014\u2014 e es\nSend Your Clothes to the\nlAODEL CLEANER\nTo be Pressed with the Latest Steam Pressing Machine\nAll Work Guaranteed\nLadies\u2019 Tailoring a Specialty\n201 MA IN ST.\na0 Mg OPtifan 5 139 North Fifth Street\nN. STILE M. D. i Graad Junction, Colo.\nP R e RT e e\nRidley-Stiles Ogtlcal Co.\nOPTIOIAN AND OCULI\nM","height":"20196","width":"16260"}}
